frameDefinitions: A Figure is located relative to a (presumably more easily located) Ground, asserting that the Figure lies (approximately) on line from the Ground whose direction is established by semantic types of the particular LUs.
The adjectives and nouns in this frame describe an Experiencer who is feeling or experiencing a particular emotional response to a Stimulus or about a Topic.
An Experiencer, Expressor, or State has a feeling of annoyance as evoked by a Stimulus or concerning a Topic.
An Experiencer has an emotion as caused by a Stimulus or concerning a Topic.
In this frame an Agent or Cause changes the consistency of a Patient from its Initial_state to a Result.
An implicit cognizer judges that a particular State_of_affairs for which a Protagonist is responsible is socially unacceptable.
frameExamples: The plane landed 10 miles due <t>north</t> of Lake Travis in an empty field .
Mr. Whiskers is <t>upset</t> that there are no more cat treats.
I fall asleep hours later to the sound of their <t>engrossed</t> murmuring.
Donna <t>thinned</t> the soup with chicken broth.
He called it a <t>disgraceful</t> situation. INI
listRoleDefinitions: The <fen>Ground</fen> serves as a basis for describing the location of the <fen>Figure</fen>.

The <fen>Figure</fen> is perceived as located relative to a certain <fen>Ground</fen> location in a certain direction specified by the particular LU. The <fen>Figure</fen> can be an entity or an event.
The period of time during which the locative relation between <fen>Figure</fen> and <fen>Ground</fen> obtains.
The <fen>Experiencer</fen> is the person or sentient entity that experiences or feels the emotions.
The <fen>Topic</fen> is the general area in which the emotion occurs.  It indicates a range of possible <fen>Stimulus</fen>.
The <fen>Stimulus</fen> is the person, event, or state of affairs that evokes the emotional response in the <fen>Experiencer</fen>.

The <fen>State</fen> is the abstract noun that describes a more lasting experience by the <fen>Experiencer</fen>.
